In applications to string theory we are often interested in higher dimensional 
geometries such that locally there is a product structure involving a 
neighborhood of a degeneration of an elliptic fibration.
For example, the total space may be a higher dimensional elliptically fibered 
Calabi-Yau space or a  bundle over .
Then it may happen that there is a closed loop such that over every 
neighborhood in the loop we have one of Kodaira's degenerations, but upon 
going around the loop the exceptional curves get permuted.
Using the fact that the permuted curves intersect if and only if the original 
curves intersect and otherwise the same arguments as before (in particular,
matching of multiplicities), we see that a folding of an affine ADE diagram 
can be assigned in any such case, independently of whether we have a 
description in terms of a top.



Before proceeding to the classification of tops, let us also discuss the toric
interpretation of the vertices of a top  in the plane .
These are just the vertices of the polygon .
In terms of the geometry of the elliptic curve determined by  every 
such vertex  gives rise to  divisors (i.e., points) in the elliptic 
curve where  is the length of the edge of  dual to .
In the context of  there are  sections of the fibration for generic 
values of the coefficients.
If  is part of a three or higher dimensional reflexive polytope, 
 determines a divisor  in the corresponding Calabi-Yau hypersurface 
that may be reducible or irreducible.
In the latter case this divisor projects to an -fold cover of the base 
space of the fibration.
In the case of a three dimensional reflexive polytope,  consists of 
curves in the corresponding K3 if  is interior to an edge and is 
irreducible if  is a vertex of the three dimensional polytope.













Classification 

The classification of reflexive polygons is well known.
As we make extensive use of it, the resulting 16 polygons are shown in
figure .
More recently, a general algorithm for classifying reflexive polytopes
was developed and successfully applied to the 
three and four dimensional cases.


 [!tbp]
 
The 16 two-dimensional reflexive polygons. 
The polygons  are respectively dual to the polygons
, and the polygons  are self-dual. 

The main idea of the algorithm of is to look for a set of
maximal polytopes that contain all others; these are dual
to minimal polytopes that do not contain any other reflexive
polytopes.
In the present case of classifying tops, we lose the symmetry between
the objects we are trying to classify and their duals.
Given that the duals are infinite, we will obviously look for maximal
objects among the duals and minimal objects among the tops themselves.
As every dual  of a top must be contained in a prism over one
of the 16 polygons of figure , it is natural to treat
these prisms as the maximal polyhedra.

We have already drastically reduced the  group of
isomorphisms between tops by demanding that  lie in the plane
.
A further reduction comes from making a specific choice of coordinates
for .
The remaining freedom is in the subgroup  of  that fixes 
